history.content:
I think the main difference is that the Stable Marriage algorithm isn't covered, but there might be more.

---------------------------------------------------

Insofar as last summer's discrete math portion is concerned (which is what I can talk the most about), stable marriage was the only substantial difference.  I believe that there weren't any major differences in the probability section--though what motivating examples each lecturer uses may change from semester to semester (for example, Professors Song and Sinclair tend to use derangements as an example in the counting section, which I haven't seen anyone else use).
I think the main difference is that the Stable Marriage algorithm isn't covered, but there might be more.

I'm just curious, since I'm trying to get involved in course staff for 70 eventually, but I took the class over the summer and I saw my friends last semester occasionally studying a couple things that we didn't go over then. I know stable marriage is a big topic that is cut out, but is there anything else that was cut short or taught in less depth?
history.subject: what is taught in cs70 over fall/spring that is not taught over the summer?
